column63: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column169: We arrived at delivery and after they checked the freight they immediately exited the vehicle and advised that they detected a leak in the valve area of the cylinder so they were refusing the shipment. The doors of the truck were closed/locked and the vehicle was relocated to an empty parking lot on the consignee's property. FedEx Custom Critical (FDCC) contacted a local clean up agency to come on-site to see if the valve could be adjusted to stop the leak or place the cylinder in the delivery facility's pressurized encapsulator for transit back to the shipper. FDCC was notified of the release at 1520. The hazmat response vendor sent a first set of crew to secure the site, they arrived at about 1600. The second set of workers with the appropriate gear arrived at 2115. They were able to adjust the valve which stopped the leak/release of materials. The advised the freight would be secure for transport back to the shipper and would not need to be in the encapsulator.
column170: The cylinder was travelling in a metal cage to secure it and protect the cylinder/valve, so I think the only thing that could be done would be to verify the valve is properly attached/close prior to being given to the transportation provider.

At ~1900 hours, a Veolia driver picked up a tanker of DMF and piperidine to move it to a 3rd party transporter yard. The manway cover was not secure allowing liquid to spill from the tanker onto the soil. The Veolia emergency response number was called and EnviroServe was dispatched. EnviroServe estimated the spill affected 2000' X 10' of dirt. The affected soil was collected into roll off dumpsters for disposal. The NRC and CDPHE Emergency Reporting were contacted and Veolia received a call from the City and County of Denver Environmental Quality Duty Officer.
column170: To avoid a reoccurrence, Veolia is in the process of implementing the use of written checklists for post-loading and pre-shipment inspections of cargo tank motor vehicles.

On November 6, 2024, a spill incident occurred at the Heidtman Butler facility involving an overfill of a tanker truck. During a product transfer operation, the driver failed to actively monitor the flow from the dome of the tanker truck, which is required to prevent overflow. Instead, the driver was standing at the back of the trailer, timing the transfer rather than visually overseeing the product flow from the dome. As a result, approximately 300 gallons of ferrous chloride solution (372 pounds) overflowed from the tanker, spilling onto the facility’s limestone gravel bed.

column169: On 11/26/2024 at approximately 1445, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4652518 at the station location in Ontario, reporting undeclared hazardous materials.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box containing one glass jar, containing a clear liquid.  The shipment's commodity description was "bunker fuel".  Using an online safety data sheet, Dangerous Goods Administration classified the bunker fuel as UN1268 Petroleum distillates.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA regulations, as it did not display the required markings, labeling, packaging or paperwork.  The shipment is being held for an FAA investigation.

column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column169: On 11/11/2024, 0835 hours, personnel in the CSXT Yard in Montgomery, Alabama discovered GATX 33805, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Southern States Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-11-11-00087).   Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disk in the car’s non-reclosing pressure relief device had ruptured and approximately one gallon of product has slosh leaked onto the top of the car as a result. Contractor personnel replaced the blown rupture disk, verified a surge protector was present, confirmed appropriate outage in the tank, and decontaminated the top of the car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Clay Chester (912-944-7107).

On 11/4/2024 at approximately 1015, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 240946 at the station location in Spokane, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 4 plastic bottles, packaged in a fiberboard box.  The shipment was discovered emitting an odor during sort.  Further investigation revealed a stain along the bottom of the box.  Upon examining the inner contents, one of the bottles appeared damp around the closure.  A safety data sheet found inside of the packaging classified the commodity as UN3082.  It appears the shipment was tendered under IATA Special Provisions A197; however, the packaging of the shipment did not comply with IATA 5.0.2.6.1.3 and 5.0.2.8., not having sufficient closure, ullage, or absorbent material.  The shipment is being held for an FAA investigation.

column169: At 0651 ET, XPO-XCL notified ERTS of a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 1 cup of Ammonium Hydrogendifluoride released from a plastic bag due to the bag ripping from underneath the pallet. The release impacted the concrete dock. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.   A contractor was dispatched and observed an estimated 0.5lb release onto the concrete dock  floor in a 2’x2’ area as a result of dunnage. The contract used a HEPA Vac to clean-up the release. The spill  product, overpacked damaged bag, impacted PPE, and HEPA Vac filter were containerized into one 55-gallon  DF for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste generated by the incident. No storm-drains, waterways, or  soil was involved in this incident.

column169: At 02:54 EST on 11/16, XPO-NOF contacted ERTS to report a spill of about 1 quart of "RDL 16" from a 50gal metal drum impacting the trailer floor. The drum was discovered damaged due to an unknown cause. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist with the spill as soon as possible. The spill was partially contained by terminal staff using oil-dri.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-ounces of RDL 16 product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor and stain found on area of the dock floor due to improper blocking and bracing. Contractors applied absorbents to minimize staining and containerized the damaged drum inside of 85-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

A fiberboard box with a UN spec marking and warning sticker was presented to the spill agent at the HNBA location. The spill agent checked the packing spill that contained a SDS stating the contents were UN3175 class 4. There were no DG markings or paperwork attached for transportation. The shipment was placed into a steel salvage package and is being held at the location.

column169: At 2152 ET, Carla Paul with XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XHG. It was reported that approximately 25-gallons of Dibromo-3-NITRILOPROPION AMIDE released from a plastic drum due to a forklift puncture. The release impacted inside of trailer #3117679 and asphalt. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are not capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site.  A contractor was dispatched and observed an estimated release of 20-gallons onto the wooden trailer floor in a 10’x5’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer in a 20’x5’ area. The contractor neutralized the release soda ash and absorbed the spill with oil dry. The damaged drum was overpacked into an 85-gallon DF. The neutralized impacted absorbents and pallet pieces were containerized into two 55-gallon DF’s. All waste generated was left on-site for XPO to manage. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: On November 3,2024, TAG inspected trailer LTIA 253701, booking SEA 1070024. This load sailed NB on the Midnight Sun Voyage 24173 that departed Tacoma on 10/31/2024. This item was not manifested or submitted for approval and the trailer sailed with undeclared hazardous material inside on the Vessel.
column170: The bill of lading for this shipment in question was not completed correctly by Lynden's shipper. This incident resulted in an internal corrective action with this shipper. Lynden's Sales team went to review with their customer to enure correct manifesting moving forward

On 11/10/2024, PNEU 418010 was loaded to the vessel without a declaration of hazardous materials(glycol residue- UN 3082, Class 9). The shipper provided a BOL identifying the hazardous material, but this was sent to the incorrect email address. Per TOTE Maritime policies, hazardous materials must be declared to and approved by our Hazardous Approvals team prior to acceptance at a TOTE terminal.
column170: This incident resulted in an internal corrective action with this shipper. The shipper provided the following corrective action: Warehouse will communicate via email to Logistics with a descriptive request that will include what the contents contained in the empty drums are, and which trailer number it will be going into. Logistics will then reach out to Tote and their Hazmat team if there are any Hazardous materials contained last. Before releasing any trailers going forward to Tote, if there are any Hazardous materials last contained, no drivers should take the trailer unless a communication via email from Tote's Hazmat team has given authorization.

column169: AT THE UPS FACILITY IN COLOGNE, GERMANY (CGN), DURING LOADING OF AN AIR CONTAINER DESTINED FOR SPAIN (MAD), AN AIR PACKAGE FROM HONG KONG TO SPAIN WAS FOUND EMITTING SMOKE AND FUMES. A STRONG SMELL WAS RECOGNIZED IN THE CONTAINER INITIATING UNLOADING OF THE CONTAINER TO FIND THE EVENT PACKAGE. ONCE FOUND THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE BUILDING AND SUNK IN A BARREL OF WATER TO STOP THE LITHIUM BATTERY EVENT. THE INCIDENT PACKAGE WAS MARKED AND LABELLED AS UN3480, LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965 WITH A CAO AND CLASS 9 LITHIUM BATTERY LABEL. THE PACKAGE WAS PART OF A MULTIPLE TEN PACKAGE SHIPMENT WITH AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AND HAD PREVIOUSLY PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT IN HONG KONG. PRIOR TO THE LITHIUM BATTERY EVENT IN COLOGNE, GERMANY, THE PACKAGE HAD PREVIOUSLY FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT FROM HKG - DXB - CGN.   THE PACKAGE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ON 14-NOVEMBER-2024, REPORT NUMBER 1416362.

At 14:02 PM ET, XDM contacted the call center to report a spill that occurred at a Fat Dog's truck stop, located at 1730 Highway 10 in Gibbon, NE. The spill consists of approximately 3 gallons or more of a UN2809 mercury, which released from a metallic cylinder contained inside of a wooden crate. The driver stated he cannot get close enough to inspect the cylinder and provide a trade name as the substance is too dangerous, and they are not in possession of a BOL either. The spill is inside the trailer and has leaked out onto the asphalt beneath the trailer. ERTS will dispatch a contractor to assist.   Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1 teaspoon of Mercury product and .5-gallon motor oil was released to trailer and asphalt due to load shift. The waste, PPE and impacted absorbents were containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly drums and Mercury waste was placed in a 5-gallon poly before it was placed in a (1) 35-gallon poly drum. The waste is staged for TSDF to pick up.

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately two (2) ounce release of product from two (2) three (3) gallon metal pail. Personnel advised they cleaned the release and generated one (1) 55-gallon poly drum containing the 2 damaged pails and spent product and absorbent. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

The drivers left the shippers facility enroute to the final destination. Upon entering highway traffic, the driver encountered vehicles that were not merging correctly and driving aggressively. They brake checked each other and the truck driver had to do emergency braking maneuver to avoid collision with the 2 other vehicles. The load shifted forward, and 2 IBCs shifted and pushed barrels together after the load securement failed. The drum of ferric chloride was crushed by one of the other barrels, causing a crack at the bottom corner of the barrel. The duration of the release was approximately 1.5 hours. The local fire department was called and was on scene along with WY DOT personnel as it happened at the Wyoming Port of Entry. The Laramie County fire department had sand delivered and built a berm and used absorbent to stop the spread of the spill.  Clean Harbors was contacted by the company to handle the remediation.  The fire department left the scene once the leak stopped and Clean Harbors was enroute from Denver, CO.  Clean Harbors unloaded the trailer in order to find the compromised drum, which was put into a 95-gallon overpack to contain and neutralize it with soda ash.  The crew then decontaminated the trailer using a mix of water and speedy dry.  All waste associated with the decontamination was then shoveled and wiped into a 55-gallon poly drum which was picked up the following day.
column170: Additional training was given to the driver. Logistics posts on van trailers are not meant to hold up to moving IBCs. It Would be nice if they had sections that were steel and not aluminum. It would be beneficial to have a hazardous materials defensive driving class focusing on having hazmat IBCs on board.

column169: On November 19th at 1715 hrs, personnel in the Buffalo & Pittsburgh Railroad's Butler Yard discovered tank car CBTX721497, a loaded tank car of Hydrocarbons, Liquid, NOS leaking from top fittings' protective housing cover.  BPRR management promptly implemented their emergency response plan and isolated the rail car.  The shipper, MPLX on behalf of Foster Gas was notified via CHEMTREC's report number 2024-11-20-00093.  Additionally, the National Response Center (report# 1416851) was contacted regarding the release of product.  Shawn Dunkle, MPLX Operations Supervisor, responded and discovered that the liquid line was partially open and the secondary closure camlock cap gasket was missing.  Mr. Dunkle closed the liquid line valve and installed a new cam lock cap gasket to secure the container.  To ensure the railcar's service equipment was working as designed, MPLX requested a post load securement test be performed.  Specialized Professional Services (SPSI) pressured up the container to 15psi and found that the liquid line valve was defective (ball valve bypass).  On 12/11/2024, SPSI performed a product transfer into tank car CBTX721426.  The car owner, CIT Group is in the process of making arrangements to replace the defective liquid line valve.  Non-Accident Report Index (NARRI); 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100 NARRI; Non-Accident Release Code 300 (Liquid Line Valve Body - Other)
column170: MPLX Management will review loading procedures with all rail yard employees.  In addition, management will spot check outbound rail cars for securement compliance.

On November 13, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1760 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately three (3) quarts of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI) to remediate the impacted site. MEI personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN1760-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents as well as the damaged product were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum which was staged onsite for future disposal by CES personnel.

At 1211ET, XPO-UVG notified ERTS of a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 2 quarts of 130 gm acetone reducer Axalta was released from a metal pail due to a forklift accident. The release impacted the concrete dock. XPO informed us that this was already cleaned up and placed into a 55-gallon metal drum which contacts product, oil dri, cardboard and gloves.

PVS Transportation driver was filling the second of 3 tanks when product started coming out the top. Product came down mainly into containment. Some product splashed onto the top of the containment wall and next to containment. Driver and operator on site performed cleanup. Tank 2 has a gauge but it appears it was not working operator told him to fill to 5940, but it overflowed when it read 5541. Operator on site was monitoring the gauge during the fill. No Injures or Exposures.

column169: On November 3, 2024, at 0533 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Shreveport, Louisiana regarding the release of Phosphoric Acid Solution. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 30 gallons of Phosphoric Acid Solution (UN1805, 8, III) from (1) 60-gallon plastic drum onto the trailer floor and outside pavement. The release was reportedly due to a puncture from a pallet, impacting a 17’ x 8’ area in the trailer and 7’ x 100’ area on the pavement. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was neutralized then cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. The damaged drum with the remaining product was placed into an overpack to move on with the client. Undamaged products were re-loaded and re-secured in the trailer. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (7) 55-gallon DF, which were then staged onsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

column169: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While doing a routine inspection at TruckStop, a leak was discovered coming from the bottom gasket on tank truck. A slow drip of product was detected on the asphalt surface beneath truck. Less than 6 ounces of nitric acid were released and contained to immediate area. Marion Environmental was dispatched to assess site. Upon arrival on site, Marion Environmental tightened the bolts on Leaking gasket which stopped the release. Absorbent material was applied to the affected asphalt, which was worked in and recovered into one 55-gallon drum. The truck was. Monitored overnight without further incident and then sent on to its destination. There were no injuries or exposures reported

column169: On November 27, 2024, at 1647 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Wisemen, AK regarding the release of EMBR18276A. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 350 gallons of EMBR18276A (UN1993, 3, II) from (1) 350-gallon metal tote onto the ground. The release was reportedly due to a loose camlock fitting, impacting 30’ x 40’ and 8’ x 15’ areas of snow. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. Impacted snow was removed and containerized. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (12) 55-gallon DM, which were then taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

Tank car GATX 109865 was reported to be leaking with visible vapor release and icing on the protective housing while in the BNSF Everett Delta yard.  The car was isolated and responders were mobilized to inspect.  Upon inspection, it was found that the sample line valve was cracked near the threads to the sample line nipple.  A Midland kit was installed to control the release.  GATX 109865 was transferred to the FURX 130095.  The cracked sample valve was removed from the car and a cap installed to secure the car for movement under an OTMA to shop for repairs.  Release estimates are based upon evaluation of outage at the time of the response in comparison to original outage.  All released Butane dissipated to atmosphere.
column170: Shipper/Car owner should investigate to determine root cause of the valve body failure.(NAR:511)

On a routine transfer operation, two Veolia employees were in the process of transferring general solvent waste from the tanker into a rail car. During this procedure, one of the employees, who was relatively new to the department and task, attempted to collect a sample by disconnecting the hose from the tanker's bottom valve.  As the employee unfastened one of the camlock's dog ears, the hose suddenly detached, resulting in an unexpected release of approximately 60 gallons of material. Fortunately, the spill was contained within the designated secondary containment area, which consisted of a concrete pad surrounded by a protective berm.  The employee who had been disconnecting the hose was directly exposed to the liquid. Following safety protocols, they immediately utilized the nearby safety shower to decontaminate. Meanwhile, the second employee promptly shut off the external valve on the tanker to halt the flow of liquid and then notified the Environmental Health and Safety (EHS) department about the incident.
column170: The Veolia facility is working to improve their training program, including initial sign off of procedures and associated train the trainer program.

A spill occurred when a Veolia employee was moving drums for transportation at a customer's site. While using the customer's drum cart, the employee noticed that the cart's feet were not fully positioned beneath the drum being moved. Recognizing the potential hazard, the employee halted the operation and attempted to properly secure the drum onto the cart. Unfortunately, during this adjustment, the cart suddenly slipped away from the drum, causing it to fall. The drum's impact with the metal feet of the cart resulted in a puncture near its top section. Reacting swiftly, the employee rotated the drum to minimize further liquid leakage. To contain the situation, the damaged drum was promptly overpacked on the customer's premises. Following this precautionary measure, the drum was successfully shipped without any additional complications.
column170: The employee will be retrained on the equipment with the focus based on hazard recognition.

column170: Shippers need to be careful when top loading freight to make sure the bottom freight can support what is being loaded on top. Also, perhaps some dunnage like cardboard on top of the pails before top freight was loaded could have helped prevent this particular event from occurring.

column169: Empty LPG UN1075 residue car (GATX21086) was heard hissing and smelling of propane.  SPSI was contacted and mobilized, arriving at 1230 hrs.  SPSI met with Mechanical Manager Clinton Simons to obtain track protection for CN Runner track (616) via blue flag, brake set, switches locked.  After safety briefing, SPSI crew climbed to top of car with MX4 to assess for leaks and applied Snoop around the PRD.  It was determined the PRD was leaking.  Crew used Indian Spring capping kit (64A) to cap off the PRD.  Snoop was reapplied to verify there were no leaks present, waited 25 minutes before checking it again.  No leaks were verified on the PRD.  Clinton Simons was notified of findings, general housekeeping was performed of work area, and crew demobilized back to shop.

column169: On 11/11/2024, at 0709 hours, personnel in the CSXT Wauhatchie Yard in Chattanooga, Tennessee, discovered PROX32359, a tank car, residue: last contained, Butane leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Centennial Energy was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2024-11-11-00010).  Marion Environmental Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an active leak from the protective housing. Upon further inspection it was found to have the B-end liquid valve partially open; and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight with no thread tape applied. The vapor valve was also found to be partially open with the secondary closure plug less than tool tight without thread tape. Contractor personnel we able to close both valves, apply thread tape to the secondary plugs and secure them with a wrench.  The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Nick Petrosky (303-370-7102, npetrosky@centennialenergy.us).

Jose Perez, CHECKER/DRIVER REG, called safety to report a spill in trailer 401481. Jose stated that when he backed to the customers dock to unload, the customer stated they would not accept the freight (UN3093, CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, OXIDIZING, N.O.S., 8 (5.1), PG II) due to a plug in the center of the top red lid being missing and the freight possibly being contaminated. Jose stated that after inspecting the tote, he found that approximately 8oz of the product had spilled out of the top lid where the plug was missing, onto the side of the tote and the trailer floor. Jose stated he did not see the  plug missing when he left the Service Center and looked in the trailer for the plug but could not find it. Jose stated the customer advised he could stay parked at dock door #1 while the cleaning crew assists in cleaning the spill in the trailer and on the tote.

The fitting used to transfer the product is equipped with a valve and air fitting to allow the operator to blow the product line celar with compressed air. The fitting also has an in-line check valve to prevent product from being released into the air line. Unfortunately the check valve was removed by personnel due to difficulties in venting the transfer hose after it had been cleared. At the time of the incident, the oeprator left the air valve partially opened. That allowed product to flow out of the fitting when the main product valve was opened.
column170: We have retrined personnel as to the SOP for the transfer of this product. The use of the in-line check valve is also being reviewed with possible modification to help prevent recurrence. ,

column169: At 1746 ET, Michael Reames with XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal NAT. Two 55-gallon poly drums were generated for waste disposal containing loose-packed product, neutralized absorbent pads, cardboard, and PPE. When driver went out to perform his pre trip at the beginning of the day he noticed liquid had dripped onto the drive tire and the pavement at 0530et. The driver put down some absorbent and then called to have a team dispatched to provide the clean up. The crew showed up around 0800et and dawned the proper PPE and made entry into the trailer. They found that a 55 gallon drum had sever rust that had damaged the integrity allowing the material to seep out. The team then removed the container and placed it into a salvage drum and then cleaned up the material that was on the floor of the trailer and that had gotten on the pavement. The absorbents were disposed of  in the proper manner. The release was less than 1 gallon and the crew was complete by 1100et.
column170: There was a safety call with the employee responsible for picking up the container and was assigned retraining on container integrity and closure.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal NMP experienced a UN2924 PQ-8 release from a 270-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 150-gallons of product released to a 53’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and an 80’ x 40’ area of the asphalt lot below due to a forklift puncture to the tote. A vac truck was dispatched which transferred the material from the damaged tote into a new one. The vac truck was then utilized to collect all free-standing liquid. Sodium bicarbonate and absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. One 55-gallon poly drum of recovered liquid product was generated. column18: AEKO KULA DBA ALOHA AIR CARGO
column169: On Friday, 11/15/2024, a shipper attempted to ship undeclared dangerous goods. The shipper, Onesource Distributors, attempted to ship the same product twice on the same day. He went to two different employees and the shipment was rejected each time. Attempt#1 Shipper arrived at approx. 0912 carrying two boxes with limited quantity labels. Our Crew Chief noticed the label and questioned the shipper. Our employee looked up the SDS sheet online, seen it was a dangerous goods product and rejected the shipment. Attempt#2 The same driver came back at approximately 1403 with a different package. Our Cargo Agent helped him and created the air waybill to accept the shipment. However, our Crew Chief who handled the first attempt noticed the same driver. She had the accepting Cargo·Agent open the package to inspect it and found that it was the same product however it was not in the original package. The shipper took everything out of the original packages and put it in one different package. The shipment was then rejected again. It was also noted that there was no DG placard displayed on the vehicle this product was transported in by highway. Pictures and screenshots will be submitted.
column170: We are in the process of advising all of our stations so that they are aware and to be diligent when accepting and inspecting cargo. For the shipper, I would recommend they get trained on how to properly ship dangerous goods by air and that they understand that their actions could have had a very different outcome.,.

column169: During the flight the AFT Iav smoke detector went off. The FA's knocked on the door and the passenger in the Iav did not want to open the door at first immediately. She open the door and claimed her laptop(which was with her in the Iav) had started smoking. The Laptop was placed in TCB as a precaution, the passenger did not want to relinquish her laptop at first. FA's did not witness any smoke coming from the laptop; it is suspected the passenger may have been vaping in the Iav in actuality and that, that is how the smoke detector was activated. Upon landing, the passenger did not want to deplane without her laptop. The Passenger claimed United was stealing it from her. Police had to be called.

On 11/7/2024 at approximately 2100, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5029982 at the ramp facility in Atlanta, reporting a flammable liquid spill.  The shipment consisted of 2 fiberboard boxes, each containing 1 plastic jerrican.  During sort operations, one of the packages was reportedly mishandled, resulting in spillage from the closure.  The damaged package was placed in a salvage drum and the shipment awaits an amended Shipper's declaration for further transport.

Pkg Info ( TRK NBR=779787375000 PKG TYPE=Package (box/drum/jerrican/composite) PHY STATE=Liquid TRANSPORTATION PHASE=In Transit ) Commodity Info ( UNDG NBR=UN1950 CLASS=21 QTY UOM=Solid - Kilogram PSN TEXT=Aerosol, flammable PKG GRP=N/A SPILLED QTY=0 CONTAINER CAPACITY=0.4 CONTAINER UOM=Solid - Kilogram MATERIAL CONSTRUCTION=A - Metal (any type) NUMBER IN SHIPMENT=1 NUMBER FAILED=1 INNER PKG TYPE=2 - Can TOTAL AMT IN EACH CONTAINER=0.4 TOTAL UOM=Solid - Kilogram )On 11/06/2024 at approximately 2115, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5028756 at the station location in Dulles, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of several bottles of acrylic paint, two bottles of acetone, and a container of spray adhesive, all packaged in a plastic storage bin.  The shipment began to display evidence of leakage during loading.  Further investigation revealed that the undeclared acetone spilled inside of the tub.  While opening the bin to confirm spillage, roughly 84 bottles of acrylic leather paint and a can of spray adhesive was also discovered.  The bin did not appear to be prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the required markings. labeling. packaging and paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.
